1
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:32,073
THE SCHPOUNTZ

2
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:51,077
It's always the same thing
and always will be.

3
00:01:51,240 --> 00:01:55,870
We'll never ever know
who left the basket of croissants

4
00:01:56,040 --> 00:01:59,032
under the tap of the oil can.

5
00:01:59,200 --> 00:02:03,159
And however much I investigate,
I'll never find the culprit.

6
00:02:03,440 --> 00:02:06,034
Well I know it wasn't me.

7
00:02:06,200 --> 00:02:08,270
I was at Mass.
It wasn't me either.

8
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:10,433
Who then?

9
00:02:10,600 --> 00:02:13,831
Maybe a customer,
who wanted a croissant,

10
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,389
unwittingly pulled
the croissant basket in such a way

11
00:02:16,560 --> 00:02:21,190
that it ended up
under the tap of the oil can.

12
00:02:21,400 --> 00:02:22,879
Did you have a croissant?

13
00:02:23,040 --> 00:02:26,032
Sure I had one.
For breakfast, to feed myself.

14
00:02:26,200 --> 00:02:28,430
- No way!
- What do you mean, no way?

15
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:32,195
You eat but you don't feed yourself.
I'm the one who feeds you!

16
00:02:32,360 --> 00:02:34,749
Your father, my brother,
wouldn't have.

17
00:02:34,920 --> 00:02:37,388
No one pulled the wool
over his eyes.

18
00:02:37,560 --> 00:02:39,710
- As you often tell me.
- To no avail.

19
00:02:39,880 --> 00:02:41,996
Then why tell me again?

20
00:02:42,160 --> 00:02:44,913
Oh, I know I'm wrong!

21
00:02:45,080 --> 00:02:47,913
Wrong to think
you'll ever know you must work!

22
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:50,548
And that being a grocer
is an honest trade!

23
00:02:50,720 --> 00:02:54,156
And that a big boy of 25
could help his uncle,

24
00:02:54,320 --> 00:02:58,757
who houses and feeds him
despite being driven totally nuts!

25
00:02:58,920 --> 00:03:02,879
I know where you're going.
Now you'll call me a good-for-nothing.

26
00:03:03,040 --> 00:03:06,828
"Good-for-nothing"
would be too good for you!

27
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:09,195
You're a terrible-at-everything!

28
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:11,999
If you don't understand me,
then I do!

29
00:03:12,160 --> 00:03:15,914
I do understand you,
and I'm deeply hurt.

30
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:19,675
See how he is.

31
00:03:19,840 --> 00:03:22,354
Pulling faces
and not taking in a word.

32
00:03:22,520 --> 00:03:24,636
At least your brother's grateful.

33
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:29,032
He works in the shop
and realises when we're in trouble.

34
00:03:29,200 --> 00:03:32,272
He managed to sell that tub
of mouldy anchovies

35
00:03:32,440 --> 00:03:35,671
to Mr Carbonnières,
which was quite a feat!

36
00:03:35,840 --> 00:03:40,152
They were so green and bloated,
you'd have taken them for mackerel.

37
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:42,709
Well, he managed to sell them!

38
00:03:42,880 --> 00:03:44,359
Is Mr Carbonnières blind?

39
00:03:44,680 --> 00:03:46,716
I told him they were tropical.

40
00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:50,509
That's thinking
and imagination for you!

41
00:03:50,680 --> 00:03:51,999
He came up with that.

42
00:03:52,160 --> 00:03:55,675
I know very well
what got his imagination working!

43
00:03:55,840 --> 00:03:56,511
What?

44
00:03:56,720 --> 00:04:00,633
You knew that if you didn't sell them
we'd end up eating them.

45
00:04:00,800 --> 00:04:02,916
Here, on this very table.

46
00:04:03,080 --> 00:04:06,470
We'd have had tropical anchovies
every single day

47
00:04:06,640 --> 00:04:08,949
until the tub was gone

48
00:04:09,120 --> 00:04:12,317
and until this fine family's funeral.

49
00:04:12,480 --> 00:04:13,276
Meaning?

50
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:14,999
This liver paste

51
00:04:15,160 --> 00:04:18,152
is the one customers won't buy
because it's off.

52
00:04:18,320 --> 00:04:22,029
Here it is, with a hint of sourness,
to feed me.

53
00:04:22,200 --> 00:04:25,033
But I'm not stupid.
I'd rather eat rat poison.

54
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:27,270
And that roast pork is putrid.

55
00:04:27,440 --> 00:04:30,318
The only person to eat it
is Mrs Graziani.

56
00:04:30,480 --> 00:04:35,031
I say "is" today, but tomorrow
maybe I'll have to say "was"!

57
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:37,031
After eating it, she went to bed.

58
00:04:37,200 --> 00:04:40,351
She's probably rolling around
in agony now.

59
00:04:40,520 --> 00:04:42,829
Rest in peace, Mrs Graziani.

60
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:47,152
Irénée, she's 76
and has a mild dose of indigestion.

61
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:50,710
She'd need no sense
of sight, smell or taste

62
00:04:50,880 --> 00:04:54,429
to end up with indigestion
from a heaving lump of meat!

63
00:04:54,760 --> 00:04:57,593
You'll have to tie the rest
to the plate.

64
00:04:57,760 --> 00:05:00,115
Or it'll walk off during the night.

65
00:05:00,280 --> 00:05:01,156
What rubbish!

66
00:05:01,640 --> 00:05:03,392
Let him talk, Clarisse.

67
00:05:03,560 --> 00:05:06,199
His exaggeration is proof
of his absurdity.

68
00:05:06,360 --> 00:05:10,558
This meat is excellent
and I woofed it down.

69
00:05:10,720 --> 00:05:13,075
But you're used to it.

70
00:05:13,240 --> 00:05:15,515
When it comes to food poisoning,

71
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:18,274
you're immunised, fortified,
armour-plated.

72
00:05:18,440 --> 00:05:20,874
He swallows, digests
and distils poison.

73
00:05:21,040 --> 00:05:24,828
He's a veritable still,
belonging to the Borgias!

74
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:27,468
You dare call me a still!

75
00:05:27,640 --> 00:05:31,997
- Irénée, if your uncle gets mad...
- He'll start choking again.

76
00:05:32,160 --> 00:05:36,119
And that would upset me.
For despite his savage way with me...

77
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:38,238
I'm very fond of him.

78
00:05:40,480 --> 00:05:42,835
Hello!
- What do you want?

79
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:45,995
Any more of those tropical anchovies?

80
00:05:46,160 --> 00:05:49,436
- Sorry, we're right out.
- When will you get some in?

81
00:05:49,680 --> 00:05:52,148
Oh, they take a lot of time.

82
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:56,108
In 2 to 3 months,
when they're nice and ripe!

83
00:05:56,360 --> 00:05:58,749
- Where can I find them?
- Impossible.

84
00:05:58,920 --> 00:06:00,990
- House speciality.
- Too bad.

85
00:06:01,240 --> 00:06:03,117
Thanks all the same.
Goodbye.

86
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:04,952
Goodbye to you.

87
00:06:07,600 --> 00:06:10,717
Well done!
There's a lesson for you!

88
00:06:10,880 --> 00:06:12,359
Admire his work.

89
00:06:12,520 --> 00:06:15,353
We've been hit by catastrophe,
by disaster.

90
00:06:15,520 --> 00:06:17,909
50 kilos of anchovies
quietly gone bad.

91
00:06:18,480 --> 00:06:21,552
But he turns disaster
into a house speciality.

92
00:06:21,720 --> 00:06:25,474
He creates a new fish,
one not even God thought of.

93
00:06:25,640 --> 00:06:27,790
And it becomes a brand new nibble.

94
00:06:28,040 --> 00:06:31,749
Then he was wrong to sell
the whole lot to one grocer.

95
00:06:31,920 --> 00:06:33,672
Because his brand new nibble

96
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:36,718
will empty the village
of its population.

97
00:06:36,880 --> 00:06:39,678
All poisoned by his new fish.

98
00:06:39,920 --> 00:06:43,151
You have to denigrate his initiative!

99
00:06:43,320 --> 00:06:46,835
Well done, Casimir.
Here's 10 francs to buy a treat.

100
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:50,998
Pay no heed
to this useless idiot's sarcasm.

101
00:06:51,240 --> 00:06:52,878
I could get so angry...

102
00:06:53,040 --> 00:06:54,871
No! You'll start choking.

103
00:06:55,040 --> 00:06:58,430
I don't mind choking
if it's to correct his rubbish!

104
00:06:58,600 --> 00:07:02,957
My God! It's unthinkable:
A man who doesn't want to work.

105
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:07,636
I don't want to work in a grocery!
When I'm in your shop...

106
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:11,270
Not a shop, a store!
How many more times?

107
00:07:11,440 --> 00:07:15,194
OK. When I'm in your store
between dry fish and wet cheese,

108
00:07:15,360 --> 00:07:16,793
it makes me queasy.

109
00:07:16,960 --> 00:07:19,997
Discussing potatoes
with Mrs Leribouchon,

110
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:23,516
who always wants a penny off,
doesn't interest me.

111
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:27,036
- I wasn't born to do that!
- To do what then?

112
00:07:27,200 --> 00:07:30,158
Another career.
I'm sure I have a gift.

113
00:07:30,320 --> 00:07:32,834
If you have anything,
it's not a gift.

114
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:35,434
You never buy anything sensible
with your pay.

115
00:07:35,600 --> 00:07:39,388
I mean a natural gift, a born gift,
a gift from God!

116
00:07:39,560 --> 00:07:42,154
Glad to hear you have
a God-given gift.

117
00:07:42,320 --> 00:07:45,915
Other than your big appetite,
big mouth and laziness,

118
00:07:46,080 --> 00:07:48,355
I do wonder what God gave you.

119
00:07:48,520 --> 00:07:51,318
Talent. Hidden talent.

120
00:07:51,480 --> 00:07:52,754
Very well hidden!

121
00:07:52,920 --> 00:07:54,069
I know.

122
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:57,391
If you break your promise
you'll dishonour yourself.

123
00:07:57,720 --> 00:08:00,996
I won't tell. I'm just saying
you have hidden talent.

124
00:08:01,160 --> 00:08:02,673
As I've long known.

125
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:06,276
And what might this talent bring in?

126
00:08:06,440 --> 00:08:07,873
Millions, of course.

127
00:08:08,040 --> 00:08:10,031
- Millions of what?
- Francs.

128
00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:14,558
- Now he has delusions of grandeur!
- I knew you wouldn't believe me.

129
00:08:14,720 --> 00:08:17,598
Do you know how much dry fish
you must sell

130
00:08:17,760 --> 00:08:19,955
to earn a million francs?

131
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:22,509
No. And I don't want to know.

132
00:08:22,680 --> 00:08:25,353
But I know I'll make millions

133
00:08:25,520 --> 00:08:27,715
because I have a talent.

134
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:33,991
If he said that, he must be mad.

135
00:08:34,160 --> 00:08:37,197
He's not mad, he's a schpountz.

136
00:08:37,360 --> 00:08:38,349
What's a schpountz?

137
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:40,389
Is there a schpountz around?

138
00:08:40,560 --> 00:08:44,314
Yes. The bellboy told me
he looks like Charles Boyer.

139
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:47,552
And that if we gave him a chance
to be on screen...

140
00:08:47,840 --> 00:08:50,513
I spoke to the one
in golfing trousers.

141
00:08:50,680 --> 00:08:52,238
He's the director of the film.

142
00:08:52,680 --> 00:08:54,875
Come over here, you idiot.

143
00:08:55,760 --> 00:08:57,398
Have you looked in a mirror?

144
00:08:57,560 --> 00:09:01,314
Potato nose, cauliflower ears,
pigeon toes...

145
00:09:01,480 --> 00:09:04,153
- Is that Charles Boyer?
- My sister told me...

146
00:09:04,320 --> 00:09:06,834
Go on, clear off!

147
00:09:07,520 --> 00:09:09,954
I hadn't noticed he was an idiot.

148
00:09:10,200 --> 00:09:13,033
Good sir, a schpountz isn't an idiot.

149
00:09:13,200 --> 00:09:16,795
A schpountz is logical
and lives an ordinary life.

150
00:09:16,960 --> 00:09:19,793
He even has common sense,
except regarding cinema.

151
00:09:20,080 --> 00:09:24,119
If he thinks he looks like an actor,
he'll believe so for ever.

152
00:09:24,440 --> 00:09:28,149
Play any trick you like,
he won't think you're poking fun.

153
00:09:28,920 --> 00:09:30,273
Do you meet many?

154
00:09:30,560 --> 00:09:31,788
One or two a day.

155
00:09:32,200 --> 00:09:34,270
If he's not mad,
he must be an idiot.

156
00:09:34,520 --> 00:09:36,078
Not at all.

157
00:09:36,240 --> 00:09:37,355
Come now, Miss...

158
00:09:37,680 --> 00:09:39,557
What's in that bellboy's head?

159
00:09:39,720 --> 00:09:42,678
If there was
the slightest resemblance,

160
00:09:42,840 --> 00:09:45,718
a single family trait
in common with Mr Boyer,

161
00:09:45,880 --> 00:09:47,996
a similarity in the voice,

162
00:09:48,160 --> 00:09:51,197
like mine and Mr Raimu's,
then I'd understand.

163
00:09:51,440 --> 00:09:52,714
But he has nothing.

164
00:09:52,880 --> 00:09:56,589
- Whereas you sound like Raimu.
- They have the self-same voice!

165
00:09:56,880 --> 00:09:59,792
That's why you looked at me so oddly
when we met.

166
00:10:00,040 --> 00:10:02,679
- Because you have Raimu's voice.
- Strikingly so!

167
00:10:02,960 --> 00:10:04,075
I'm not a schpountz?

168
00:10:04,320 --> 00:10:05,833
Not at all!

169
00:10:06,560 --> 00:10:09,233
It's not just the voice,
but his look,

170
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:11,755
his gait, his unabashed kindness...

171
00:10:11,920 --> 00:10:13,148
Everything!

172
00:10:13,320 --> 00:10:17,598
Not everything. There isn't room.
I have my own personality too.

173
00:10:17,840 --> 00:10:20,308
You could play parts
that he couldn't.

174
00:10:20,960 --> 00:10:22,473
Mr Raimu would agree.

175
00:10:22,640 --> 00:10:24,949
And he would play some parts
better than I.

176
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:27,111
- Who knows?
- Exactly.

177
00:10:27,360 --> 00:10:30,397
And yet it's obvious
he isn't a schpountz.

178
00:10:30,720 --> 00:10:31,516
I can prove it.

179
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:35,719
I know you're making a film.
Have I asked for a part in it?

180
00:10:35,880 --> 00:10:38,394
- Not yet.
- And I never will.

181
00:10:38,640 --> 00:10:42,030
- What if we asked you?
- I'd be forced to refuse.

182
00:10:42,200 --> 00:10:44,156
Your manager would forbid it?

183
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:48,599
I don't care about the manager,
but I have my barman's duties.

184
00:10:48,760 --> 00:10:51,797
Earlier you said I had Raimu's voice.

185
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:55,436
If I look at that
from a personal point of view,

186
00:10:55,600 --> 00:10:57,511
then Mr Raimu has MY voice!

187
00:10:57,680 --> 00:10:59,830
And though it's mine, I can't use it.

188
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:05,199
Because he acted in public before me
and I wouldn't like to wrong him.

189
00:11:05,440 --> 00:11:07,032
- Yes, but...
- No buts!

190
00:11:07,280 --> 00:11:09,714
I don't have the right!

191
00:11:11,760 --> 00:11:14,035
Now that's a 1st-class schpountz!

192
00:11:14,360 --> 00:11:15,918
But we've seen better ones!

193
00:11:16,680 --> 00:11:19,240
You should tell Uncle
about your talent.

194
00:11:19,400 --> 00:11:21,277
He knows nothing about cinema.

195
00:11:21,440 --> 00:11:23,237
He went twice with Auntie.

196
00:11:23,400 --> 00:11:27,678
The first time he said it was stupid,
the second time he dozed off.

197
00:11:28,120 --> 00:11:32,079
- He went though.
- But he was hardly enthralled.

198
00:11:32,280 --> 00:11:34,475
Can I tell him my talent is acting?

199
00:11:34,640 --> 00:11:37,837
No, Casimir.
No premature revelations!

200
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:39,911
No upsetting the honest grocer!

201
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:43,356
- He might try to discourage you.
- Discourage me?

202
00:11:44,200 --> 00:11:45,474
Don't be silly.

203
00:11:45,640 --> 00:11:48,791
I know I was born
with a gift for acting.

204
00:11:48,960 --> 00:11:50,757
God has given me the chance

205
00:11:50,920 --> 00:11:54,913
to see my name on posters
and up in lights.

206
00:11:55,080 --> 00:11:57,674
And the dollars... The dollars!

207
00:11:57,840 --> 00:11:59,512
Doesn't "dollars" sound pretty?

208
00:11:59,680 --> 00:12:02,274
Once, in a bank window
in Marseilles,

209
00:12:02,440 --> 00:12:05,238
I saw a 100-dollar bill.
It didn't look pretty.

210
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:07,038
They didn't give it to you!

211
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:10,510
You have no English.
Why will they give you dollars?

212
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:14,753
Because of my acting talent.
The film industry is full of dollars!

213
00:12:14,920 --> 00:12:19,311
<i>For You always talks about it.
So if God sends me my chance...</i>

214
00:12:19,480 --> 00:12:20,708
But how?

215
00:12:20,960 --> 00:12:23,838
I don't know. But He owes me one.

216
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:26,992
Does God toil away for nothing?

217
00:12:27,160 --> 00:12:30,277
Would He have given me
this calling, this memory,

218
00:12:30,440 --> 00:12:32,556
this voice, this gait,

219
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:35,109
this quivering sensitivity,

220
00:12:35,280 --> 00:12:37,714
to leave me serving gorgonzola?

221
00:12:37,880 --> 00:12:40,952
No, Casimir.
God isn't mad!

222
00:12:41,120 --> 00:12:45,955
Despite his games of famine,
war, floods and plague,

223
00:12:46,120 --> 00:12:49,237
God is basically someone
with good common sense.

224
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:52,119
At His age,
I'd be surprised if He didn't.

225
00:12:52,280 --> 00:12:54,953
So I won't go looking for my chance.

226
00:12:55,120 --> 00:12:56,872
I'll wait for it right here.

227
00:12:59,880 --> 00:13:01,632
- Casimir!
- Yes?

228
00:13:01,800 --> 00:13:04,268
- Are you up?
- No. But I won't be long.

229
00:13:04,440 --> 00:13:07,159
It's only 8 o'clock.
And it's Sunday.

230
00:13:07,320 --> 00:13:09,959
I know, but go down anyway.

231
00:13:11,720 --> 00:13:14,518
- Uncle, are you up?
- No.

232
00:13:14,680 --> 00:13:17,194
Then why torture poor Casimir?

233
00:13:17,360 --> 00:13:21,672
There are cars driving past.
We need someone in the store.

234
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:24,832
I'll go.
You stay in bed, Casimir.

235
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:28,356
I'll do the exceptional job
of working on Sunday.

236
00:13:28,520 --> 00:13:29,714
He'll have no reproach.

237
00:13:29,880 --> 00:13:32,713
He wants the store open,
so I'll open it.

238
00:13:32,880 --> 00:13:34,438
Anyway, I'm starving.

239
00:14:19,040 --> 00:14:22,828
- What's wrong?
- We're running on steam!

240
00:14:23,760 --> 00:14:26,399
- What will you do?
- Put some water in.

241
00:14:31,520 --> 00:14:32,839
I'll look for some.

242
00:14:46,200 --> 00:14:47,599
Anyone here?

243
00:14:54,680 --> 00:14:57,319
- Hey, what are you doing?
- The saucepan...

244
00:14:57,480 --> 00:14:59,311
Yes, saucepan to sell.

245
00:14:59,480 --> 00:15:02,153
- Of course...
- More than that it's...

246
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:03,992
65 francs.

247
00:15:04,600 --> 00:15:07,194
No, look... 6 francs 50.

248
00:15:07,400 --> 00:15:09,470
No, look closer... 65 centimes.

249
00:15:09,640 --> 00:15:11,551
Tinplated top-class steel,

250
00:15:11,720 --> 00:15:14,188
nice shape and practical.
6 francs 50.

251
00:15:14,360 --> 00:15:18,353
The enamel won't crack,
as there is no enamel. 6 francs 50.

252
00:15:18,520 --> 00:15:22,991
- I just want to fill my radiator.
- Which means you have a car.

253
00:15:23,160 --> 00:15:25,833
If so, 6 francs 50 is nothing to you.

254
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:28,468
I've no change.
Plus it's for the cinema.

255
00:15:28,640 --> 00:15:31,108
- You own a cinema?
- No. I make films.

256
00:15:31,280 --> 00:15:34,716
- You do? Where? When?
- Here. Today.

257
00:15:34,880 --> 00:15:37,110
You make films. I knew it!

258
00:15:37,280 --> 00:15:39,794
I've been expecting you.
I'll help you.

259
00:15:39,960 --> 00:15:43,111
God most definitely isn't mad.

260
00:15:43,520 --> 00:15:45,511
This way.
He isn't mad at all!

261
00:15:50,320 --> 00:15:52,675
Now he's saying God isn't mad.

262
00:15:52,840 --> 00:15:55,593
But he's completely round the twist.

263
00:15:57,640 --> 00:16:00,598
- I'll give you that saucepan.
- You're too kind.

264
00:16:02,520 --> 00:16:04,988
He's lending a saucepan
to some clown

265
00:16:05,160 --> 00:16:07,355
dressed in my grandma's trousers.

266
00:16:19,600 --> 00:16:22,956
This is the first time
I've ever been in a car.

267
00:16:24,840 --> 00:16:26,034
Driver!

268
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:28,109
Driver!

269
00:16:28,800 --> 00:16:30,552
Take the next left!

270
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:53,353
Chaps, here you are.

271
00:16:53,520 --> 00:16:56,671
At the Col de Tantoi.
There it is.

272
00:16:56,840 --> 00:16:58,398
It looks a bit funny!

273
00:16:58,560 --> 00:17:00,118
Well, thank you so much.

274
00:17:00,280 --> 00:17:02,510
My pleasure.
Where are the actors?

275
00:17:02,680 --> 00:17:05,194
- Not here yet.
- So you're not filming yet?

276
00:17:05,360 --> 00:17:08,716
- No. In about 2 or 3 hours time.
- And until then?

277
00:17:08,880 --> 00:17:12,429
We'll play cards and have a bite
until we start.

278
00:17:12,600 --> 00:17:13,715
I see.

279
00:17:13,880 --> 00:17:17,475
If you'll allow,
I'd like to watch the filming.

280
00:17:17,640 --> 00:17:20,108
But now I've shown you the col,

281
00:17:20,280 --> 00:17:23,033
I'll go home and put on my collar!

282
00:17:23,760 --> 00:17:25,955
Madam, gentlemen...

283
00:17:26,440 --> 00:17:27,873
See you later.

284
00:17:36,160 --> 00:17:39,232
This is it. It has to be.

285
00:17:39,560 --> 00:17:41,869
- You doubt me.
- No, I don't.

286
00:17:42,040 --> 00:17:44,679
I doubt the others.
They may not understand.

287
00:17:44,840 --> 00:17:46,239
I'll make them understand.

288
00:17:46,400 --> 00:17:49,870
I showed them the way.
I told them I'd be back.

289
00:17:50,040 --> 00:17:52,429
This is the chance of a lifetime!

290
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:54,352
And I'm ready.

291
00:17:54,520 --> 00:17:57,159
I'm in my suit and tie...
No, I'm not!

292
00:17:57,400 --> 00:18:00,278
I'm in my tie,
I've found my moustache.

293
00:18:00,440 --> 00:18:04,194
And the best thing of all:
They've only seen me in my pyjamas!

294
00:18:04,360 --> 00:18:08,114
I'll make an extraordinary entrance.
I'll send them reeling.

295
00:18:08,280 --> 00:18:10,396
- Like lightning.
- How?

296
00:18:10,560 --> 00:18:13,120
With a centre parting.

297
00:18:13,560 --> 00:18:15,198
What will you say?

298
00:18:15,880 --> 00:18:20,078
I plan to be humble
and thus obtain an audition.

299
00:18:20,240 --> 00:18:23,437
- What if they laugh?
- At what?

300
00:18:23,920 --> 00:18:25,717
- You.
- Me?

301
00:18:26,480 --> 00:18:28,311
Irénée, I didn't mean to say...

302
00:18:28,480 --> 00:18:31,233
But you did!
You don't believe in me.

303
00:18:31,400 --> 00:18:34,198
Go, false brother.
I'll look after myself!

304
00:18:34,360 --> 00:18:36,920
I do believe in you.
But not as much as you do.

305
00:18:37,080 --> 00:18:39,514
Meaning?
Spit it out, you renegade!

306
00:18:39,680 --> 00:18:41,750
Things never move so quickly.

307
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:46,791
It's hardly likely they'll hire you
and make you an immediate star.

308
00:18:46,960 --> 00:18:49,269
You need to plot out a path

309
00:18:49,440 --> 00:18:52,352
and take it one step at a time.

310
00:18:53,440 --> 00:18:56,432
Napoleon was a sub-lieutenant
from Corsica!

311
00:18:56,600 --> 00:18:58,033
He became Emperor.

312
00:18:58,200 --> 00:19:02,352
You don't become Emperor
one step at a time!

313
00:19:02,520 --> 00:19:03,635
You're right to go.

314
00:19:03,800 --> 00:19:06,314
I'm saying all this
out of friendship.

315
00:19:06,480 --> 00:19:09,313
I don't want you to suffer
a disappointment.

316
00:19:09,480 --> 00:19:11,710
You really are Saturday's Child.

317
00:19:11,880 --> 00:19:13,871
Born under the influence of Saturn.

318
00:19:14,040 --> 00:19:16,554
You're saturnine.
I read it in the paper!

319
00:19:16,720 --> 00:19:19,553
- So what?
- You'll never get anywhere!

320
00:19:19,840 --> 00:19:23,389
You're sad, pessimistic
and dominated by distrust!

321
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:24,754
Pity for you.

322
00:19:24,920 --> 00:19:28,754
I was born on a Thursday
under the influence of Jupiter.

323
00:19:28,960 --> 00:19:30,473
I can hope for anything.

324
00:19:30,640 --> 00:19:33,632
If I'm told I can't,
I'll carry on hoping anyway.

325
00:19:33,800 --> 00:19:35,756
So leave me to it and shut up.

326
00:19:35,920 --> 00:19:38,593
- Well, frankly...
- Frankly what?

327
00:19:38,760 --> 00:19:42,309
You're a good man but you're baleful.
So shut it, Saturnite!

328
00:19:42,480 --> 00:19:44,118
Take it from a Jupiterite!

329
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:54,592
Gentlemen, madam...

330
00:19:54,760 --> 00:19:55,988
Delighted!

331
00:19:57,320 --> 00:19:58,719
And he wasn't pushy!

332
00:19:59,800 --> 00:20:03,236
- He was too modest.
- He was wrong, very wrong!

333
00:20:05,720 --> 00:20:07,472
This is really nice!

334
00:20:10,640 --> 00:20:14,599
Give me the address of the genius
who tailored that suit!

335
00:20:14,760 --> 00:20:17,035
He's just a lowly tailor.

336
00:20:17,200 --> 00:20:21,193
I'll gladly give you his address,
but it won't help.

337
00:20:21,360 --> 00:20:25,558
Because this suit was conceived
and designed by yours truly!

338
00:20:25,720 --> 00:20:27,472
He's a real all-rounder!

339
00:20:27,720 --> 00:20:30,314
We should have him
design one for all of us!

340
00:20:32,880 --> 00:20:34,871
What a shame!

341
00:20:35,600 --> 00:20:36,476
What is?

342
00:20:36,640 --> 00:20:38,949
What a shame that a man like this,

343
00:20:39,120 --> 00:20:41,350
due to family or social commitments,

344
00:20:41,520 --> 00:20:43,909
cannot work in films.

345
00:20:44,600 --> 00:20:48,309
Whenever we find a good one,
we can't have him!

346
00:20:49,680 --> 00:20:52,672
To work in films in what quality?

347
00:20:52,840 --> 00:20:54,512
As an actor, of course.

348
00:20:54,760 --> 00:20:57,832
Looks are important for an actor.

349
00:20:58,120 --> 00:21:01,032
But so too does elegance.

350
00:21:02,040 --> 00:21:03,837
The main thing is sex appeal.

351
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:06,958
Well he has a very
sexually appealing voice!

352
00:21:07,280 --> 00:21:09,396
It may sound ridiculous,

353
00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:11,511
but I do think I have a bit.

354
00:21:11,680 --> 00:21:13,636
It just needs cultivating.

355
00:21:13,800 --> 00:21:15,438
How charmingly modest!

356
00:21:15,600 --> 00:21:17,830
I'm not modest, sir. I was.

357
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:21,117
But the day I decided
to become an artiste,

358
00:21:21,280 --> 00:21:23,032
I sacrificed modesty.

359
00:21:23,320 --> 00:21:25,550
So you'd truly like to be in films?

360
00:21:25,800 --> 00:21:28,268
Not just "like to".

361
00:21:28,440 --> 00:21:31,955
I dream of it, get sick with it,
die with it!

362
00:21:32,120 --> 00:21:35,590
Film is my passion, my folly.

363
00:21:35,760 --> 00:21:38,115
I'd do anything just for a bit part.

364
00:21:38,280 --> 00:21:41,716
Even do it for free.
The first one, at least.

365
00:21:42,320 --> 00:21:43,673
Kids, I have an idea.

366
00:21:43,840 --> 00:21:46,798
I'm surprised
no one else had it first.

367
00:21:46,960 --> 00:21:49,554
- What idea?
- The schpountz.

368
00:21:49,760 --> 00:21:52,069
He's our schpountz!

369
00:21:53,320 --> 00:21:55,754
- Of course!
- What's a schpountz?

370
00:21:57,760 --> 00:22:01,594
The schpountz
is an extraordinary part

371
00:22:01,760 --> 00:22:03,876
in an extraordinary film.

372
00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:08,199
In 5 years, we've found no actor
capable of playing it.

373
00:22:08,360 --> 00:22:09,349
Not one.

374
00:22:09,520 --> 00:22:12,478
- We tried every big star.
- All of them!

375
00:22:12,640 --> 00:22:15,598
None of the greatest screen names
can do it.

376
00:22:15,760 --> 00:22:19,116
It's a male version of Greta Garbo.

377
00:22:19,280 --> 00:22:21,430
Sir, you scare me a little.

378
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:25,195
Let's not be hasty. In life,
this chap may be a schpountz.

379
00:22:25,360 --> 00:22:26,998
But on screen?

380
00:22:27,360 --> 00:22:29,590
He'll be even more of a schpountz.

381
00:22:29,760 --> 00:22:30,954
Not sure of that!

382
00:22:31,120 --> 00:22:32,997
That's just my opinion.

383
00:22:33,160 --> 00:22:36,516
Naturally, there'll be tests.
And I may be wrong.

384
00:22:36,680 --> 00:22:40,070
When will we do these tests?

385
00:22:40,320 --> 00:22:42,470
I can do a sound test right now.

386
00:22:42,720 --> 00:22:46,508
Do you know anything by heart?
A poem, a song...

387
00:22:46,760 --> 00:22:50,275
Yes, madam. But I won't
recite a poem or sing a song.

388
00:22:50,440 --> 00:22:51,714
It would be cheating.

389
00:22:51,880 --> 00:22:55,270
For a good poem
would detract from its reciter.

390
00:22:55,440 --> 00:22:57,590
I'll perform something different,

391
00:22:57,760 --> 00:23:00,035
which will be more conclusive.

392
00:23:00,200 --> 00:23:02,919
- He's so interesting!
- Let him start.

393
00:23:03,080 --> 00:23:04,274
Thank you.

394
00:23:04,440 --> 00:23:09,434
I shall recite for you
an article from the Civil Code.

395
00:23:09,600 --> 00:23:11,431
The shortest and clearest.

396
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:15,036
Perhaps the most "cutting".

397
00:23:15,560 --> 00:23:18,518
"Those sentenced to death
will lose their heads. "

398
00:23:18,680 --> 00:23:22,673
- That's not very cheerful.
- No, it's not. But it can be.

399
00:23:22,840 --> 00:23:25,912
I will now, having been
so warmly welcomed by you,

400
00:23:26,080 --> 00:23:29,356
give you a complete demonstration
of my modest gift.

401
00:23:29,520 --> 00:23:31,875
I will, with this simple phrase,

402
00:23:32,040 --> 00:23:34,918
induce diverse feelings inside you.

403
00:23:35,080 --> 00:23:38,152
Everything will be in the expression.

404
00:23:39,040 --> 00:23:41,031
I bet he has some expressions!

405
00:23:41,280 --> 00:23:44,477
Don't jump the gun, sir.
Are you ready?

406
00:23:45,320 --> 00:23:46,514
Absolutely.

407
00:23:46,680 --> 00:23:49,513
Then I shall begin. There.

408
00:23:54,720 --> 00:23:56,153
Fear.

409
00:24:03,520 --> 00:24:05,829
"Those sentenced to death

410
00:24:06,120 --> 00:24:08,873
"will lose their heads. "

411
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:13,349
Pity.

412
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:21,877
"Those sentenced to death

413
00:24:22,080 --> 00:24:25,038
"will lose their heads. "

414
00:24:29,600 --> 00:24:32,910
Interrogative and affirmative.

415
00:24:37,760 --> 00:24:40,479
"Those sentenced to death
will lose their heads?"

416
00:24:41,720 --> 00:24:44,996
"Those sentenced to death
WILL lose their heads!"

417
00:24:45,400 --> 00:24:46,549
Good, huh?

418
00:24:46,960 --> 00:24:48,279
Excellent.

419
00:24:48,760 --> 00:24:50,352
Pensive.

420
00:24:56,520 --> 00:24:58,272
"Those sentenced to death...

421
00:24:58,720 --> 00:25:00,278
"lose their heads... "

422
00:25:01,040 --> 00:25:04,749
Keep that expression
and try not to move!

423
00:25:05,960 --> 00:25:06,836
Got it.

424
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:08,399
Comical.

425
00:25:19,760 --> 00:25:22,069
"Those sentenced to death...

426
00:25:24,040 --> 00:25:26,349
"will lose their heads. "

427
00:25:34,640 --> 00:25:37,598
Ladies and gentlemen, I will sing,
as I have a voice,

428
00:25:37,760 --> 00:25:39,159
a song I wrote

429
00:25:39,320 --> 00:25:42,437
which highlights the two facets
of my humble talent.

430
00:25:42,600 --> 00:25:44,033
- Without music?
- Sir...

431
00:25:44,280 --> 00:25:48,353
when I sing, I hear an orchestra!

432
